🔬 Technical Deep Dive & Theory

Active Directory uses Kerberos for authentication. When a user wants to access a service (like an SQL server), they request a Ticket Granting Service (TGS) from the Domain Controller.

The Cryptographic Flaw:
The Domain Controller encrypts this TGS ticket using the NTLM password hash of the Service Account running that specific service. Because any authenticated user in the domain can request a TGS for any Service Principal Name (SPN), an attacker can request these tickets, export them, and crack the encryption offline. If the service account has a weak password, the attacker recovers the plaintext password. Since Service Accounts often have excessive privileges (sometimes Domain Admin), this leads to full domain compromise.

