🛠️ Lab Report: What We Mastered

Executive Summary: Focused on Active Directory privilege escalation today by executing a Kerberoasting attack. Leveraging the low-privilege foothold I secured yesterday, I used Impacket’s GetUserSPNs.py to query the Domain Controller and successfully extracted a vulnerable Service Principal Name (SPN) ticket ($krb5tgs$23$). I then moved the hash offline to my Arch machine and cracked it using Hashcat, completely bypassing AD account lockout policies. It was a stark reminder of how combining excessive permissions with stale, weak service account passwords can instantly hand an attacker the keys to the kingdom without triggering a single alarm.

🚨 Real-World Breach Case Study: The APT29 Methodology

During multiple high-profile breaches (including solar-winds related lateral movement), Russian state-sponsored actors (APT29) utilized Kerberoasting as a primary mechanism to escalate from a compromised phished user to Domain Admin. Because requesting TGS tickets is a standard, built-in feature of Active Directory, the initial extraction generates almost zero anomalous network traffic, allowing them to crack the passwords in their own labs and log back into the target network via VPN using the newly acquired Admin credentials.

💡 Senior Researcher Insights & Future Trends

Insight: "Kerberoasting is the silent killer of AD. It is not an exploit; it is abusing the protocol exactly how it was designed to work. Defending against it isn't about patching a vulnerability, it's about strict cryptographic hygiene."

Future Trend (Targeted AS-REP Roasting): As defenders get better at monitoring SPN queries, attackers are pivoting to AS-REP Roasting (T1558.004), targeting user accounts that have "Do not require Kerberos preauthentication" enabled, which allows extraction of the TGT without even needing an initial foothold.

Future Trend (Cloud SPNs): We are seeing similar token-extraction and offline brute-forcing methodologies migrating to improperly configured Azure AD (Entra ID) App Registrations and Service Principals.

